    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that seems like a lot of \"if\"s though. if the transit isn't already there, aren't people just being penalized for needing to commute? it feels like some people see it as a regressive move that favors people in the city center who can walk or take the subway, while the working class gets stuck with the bill. isn't there a risk that the \"climate urgency\" is just being used as a cover to pass an unfair tax?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The risk of being perceived as an unfair tax is real, which is why the political will to implement it must be matched by robust social safety nets. If the infrastructure isn't ready, the policy fails its equity test, and the climate argument rings hollow to many. Therefore, the implementation must be phased, with the pricing mechanism directly tied to demonstrable, concurrent improvements in outer-borough transit capacity.",
      "source": "target",
